Figure 15 illustrates the carbon capture cost as a function of carbon dioxide concentrations (IEA 2022). As can be found, direct air capture, because of the lowest carbon dioxide concentration, demonstrates the most expensive capturing processes. The other key factor that specifies the carbon capture cost is the scale of capturing (Akinola et al. 2022). Routinely, the capital cost of different industrial plants increases in a nonlinear relation with scale, including carbon dioxide capture plants. On the grounds, the capital cost is correlated by scale with the power of n, where n is in the range of 0.6–0.8. Thus, the cost of two different plants is related together by (Tribe and Alpine 1986):1CostofplantA=CostofplantBCapacityofplantACapacityofplantBn0.6≤n≤0.8\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
